lyFishMN:<br>
<br>
Really the method we use to fish is pretty easy. I don't know if you saw the show on the Outdoor Channel with my 6 year old son Will or not. Although he was fishing a kids creek he landed several fish over 20&quot; and one that was 28&quot;. I'd pretty much say that if he can do it anybody can. The truest secret to fishing these rivers is setting up your rig properly. The amount of weight, length of tippet, the distance from the weight to the fly, and how high the fly drifts off the bottom are all critical to how often the fish take. They see literally thousands of bugs an hour and we try to set them up to take ours as a prefered bug. The guy in the picture caught probably close to 20-30 fish in the first hour we were at the shoal where other people were catching something along the order of 2-3 fish per hour. <br>
<br>
I guess I could sit and write an article on how I set up a rig. The problem with that is that there are so many subtle changes with it that a client never really sees when we are on the river. Fly profile, overcast days vs clear days, I guess the list goes on and on. Once you've got it you've got it though and anyone can catch these fish. However, I can say that we spent 6 hours casting to a 42&quot; brown that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>never</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> took the fly. He called me the next day and said that when he comes back he wants to catch one fish just to get the &quot;skunk off&quot;. Then he wants to spend the rest of the trip working on one of those big fish. I can relate....... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
John<br>
